snippet.textDisplay:
As a clothing designer who’s full time job is making custom clothing for people- I just wanted to give my two cents. (Before I
Give my opinion, I just wanted to preface that I am speculating and everything I say is my opinion based on what evidence I saw in the video) it appears to me based on the video commentary that what H&M means by “sustainable” is clothing using natural fibers. (“Jeans with no stretch, itchy sweaters” ect..) normally in modern day clothing there is elastane in the fibers to create stretch or “wearing ease”. I’m using Elastane as a general word for a synthetic material that makes all types of your fabric have stretch. Unfortunately, It is incredibly polluting and bad for the environment. The whole “natural fibers” thing is what I THINK H&M is trying to promote with this line. HOWEVER, there are many sides to creating sustainable clothing besides fabric choices, such as, paying people a proper wage to make their clothing and not slave wages. H&M is NOT a sustainable clothing brand and while using natural fibers is a great start toward sustainability, fast fashion in and of itself is not sustainable. Moreover, if you are interested, I also wanted to give some advice when wearing natural non-woven fibers as clothing (fabric without stretch). I actually specialize in fitting and drafting patterns made with 100% cotton denim like you saw on the video. If anyone reading this comment has ever purchased a pair or leather shoes, cowboy boots, or horseback riding boots; there is something called a “break in” period where the clothing (or shoe) is slowly softened and quite literally molded to your body over time. Having your new non stretch denim feeling tight and almost too small is NORMAL (depending on the cut and style of corse). During this break in process, the denim will feel uncomfortable but I promise you the end result is the most flattering best pair of jeans you can own. With all of that said if you want your non stretch denim to fit like a dream, here’s how I do it: your non stretch denim (depending on the cut of corse) should feel almost too tight or as if you need to go up a size. If you buy them too big, the natural fibers will stretch out over time and the result will be a loose, baggy frumpy pair of jeans, so don’t get intimidated! I actually make/purchase mine so tight I have to lay down on my bed in order to zip them up at first (think 1970s, the PRIME era for non stretch denim). This is normal. To help you start breathing normally again quicker, wear your new jeans around the house, do squats, try running. If you’re really desperate, wear your new jeans in the bath tub and let them air dry to your body. In general, these are natural woven fibers and will grow and mold over time, kind of like leather. I encourage everyone to try out non stretch denim, but give some time before casting judgement! Good luck!
